---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="CSP Builder — Build a Content Security Policy Visually | HeaderLab"
  description="Visually build a Content Security Policy header with templates, per-directive sources, and copyable Nginx, Apache, and Cloudflare snippets. Privacy-first, runs entirely in your browser."
>
  <section class="tool-header">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← All tools</a>
    <h1>CSP Builder</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Build a Content Security Policy interactively. Start from a template,
      adjust directives, see the policy update live, and copy a config snippet
      for Nginx, Apache, or Cloudflare.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="csp-templates">
    <span class="label">Start from:</span>
    <button type="button" class="tpl-btn" data-template="strict">Strict</button>
    <button type="button" class="tpl-btn" data-template="balanced">Balanced</button>
    <button type="button" class="tpl-btn" data-template="permissive">Permissive</button>
    <button type="button" class="tpl-btn reset" data-template="empty">Empty</button>
  </section>

  <section class="csp-options">
    <label>
      <input type="checkbox" id="report-only" />
      <span>Report-only mode (test without blocking — uses <code>Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only</code> header)</span>
    </label>
  </section>

  <section id="builder-grid" class="builder-grid">
    <!-- Directive cards rendered by JS -->
  </section>

  <section class="policy-preview">
    <h2>Generated policy</h2>
    <pre id="policy-output"><code></code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="fix-snippets">
    <h4>Fix it</h4>
    <div class="tabs" role="tablist">
      <button class="tab-btn active" data-target="csp-nginx">Nginx</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" data-target="csp-apache">Apache</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" data-target="csp-cloudflare">Cloudflare</button>
    </div>
    <div class="tab-panels">
      <div id="csp-nginx" class="tab-panel active">
        <div class="snippet-location">
          <strong>Where:</strong> Add inside your <code>server</code> block — e.g. <code>/etc/nginx/sites-available/yoursite</code>. Reload: <code>sudo nginx -s reload</code>
        </div>
        <div class="snippet-code">
          <button class="copy-btn" type="button">Copy</button>
          <pre><code id="snippet-nginx-code"></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div id="csp-apache" class="tab-panel">
        <div class="snippet-location">
          <strong>Where:</strong> Add to <code>.htaccess</code> in your site root, or to your <code>VirtualHost</code> config. Requires <code>mod_headers</code>.
        </div>
        <div class="snippet-code">
          <button class="copy-btn" type="button">Copy</button>
          <pre><code id="snippet-apache-code"></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div id="csp-cloudflare" class="tab-panel">
        <div class="snippet-location">
          <strong>Where:</strong> Apply via Cloudflare Dashboard. See snippet for navigation path.
        </div>
        <div class="snippet-code">
          <button class="copy-btn" type="button">Copy</button>
          <pre><code id="snippet-cloudflare-code"></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="seo-content">
    <header class="seo-intro">
      <span class="seo-tag">REFERENCE</span>
      <h2>Understanding Content Security Policy</h2>
      <p class="seo-lead">
        A practical guide to deploying CSP without breaking your site.
      </p>
    </header>

    <h3>What is Content Security Policy?</h3>
    <p>
      Content Security Policy (CSP) is an HTTP response header that tells the browser
      which sources of content — scripts, styles, images, fonts, iframes, and more —
      are allowed to load on a page. When properly configured, it dramatically reduces
      the impact of cross-site scripting (XSS), one of the most common and damaging
      web vulnerabilities.
    </p>
    <p>
      Unlike a single-purpose header like <code>X-Frame-Options</code> (which only
      controls iframing), CSP is a complete declarative policy: you list the trusted
      sources for each kind of resource, and the browser blocks anything that doesn't
      match. If an attacker manages to inject a <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag pointing
      to their own server, CSP prevents the browser from executing it.
    </p>
    <p>
      CSP is supported by all modern browsers and has been the OWASP-recommended
      primary defense against XSS for over a decade.
    </p>

    <h3>Why CSP is hard to deploy</h3>
    <p>
      CSP is powerful, but it's notoriously tricky to roll out without breaking your
      site. Most pages depend on dozens of third-party resources — analytics, fonts,
      error tracking, embedded videos, payment widgets — and missing any single one
      in your policy will silently break it. There are two practical strategies:
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Report-only first.</strong> Deploy
      <code>Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only</code> instead of the enforcing header.
      The browser will check your policy but won't block anything; instead, it'll log
      violations (and optionally POST them to a <code>report-uri</code> endpoint).
      After a few days of real traffic, you'll know exactly what your policy is missing.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Start broad, tighten over time.</strong> Begin with a permissive policy
      (<code>default-src 'self' https:</code>) and progressively restrict. Each release,
      narrow one directive based on what your site actually needs.
    </p>
    <p>
      The CSP Builder above gives you a starting policy. The
      <a href="/headers">Headers Checker</a> will then tell you whether what you
      shipped is actually being delivered by your server.
    </p>

    <h3>Directive-by-directive guide</h3>
    <p>
      CSP is made up of <em>directives</em> — individual rules for different resource
      types. Here are the most important ones:
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>default-src</code></strong> is the fallback. Any fetch directive you
      don't explicitly set inherits from <code>default-src</code>. Setting it to
      <code>'self'</code> is a reasonable safe baseline; setting it to <code>'none'</code>
      (GitHub's choice) is the strictest possible default and forces you to explicitly
      allow each resource type.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>script-src</code></strong> controls where JavaScript can come from.
      This is the most security-critical directive. Avoid <code>'unsafe-inline'</code>
      and <code>'unsafe-eval'</code> — they essentially turn off CSP's XSS protection.
      If you need inline scripts, use nonces (<code>'nonce-abc123'</code>) or hashes
      (<code>'sha256-...'</code>).
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>style-src</code></strong> controls stylesheets. Many modern
      frameworks (Tailwind, CSS-in-JS libraries) inject inline styles, so
      <code>'unsafe-inline'</code> here is extremely common and significantly less
      dangerous than in <code>script-src</code> — attackers can't execute code through
      CSS, only modify appearance.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>img-src</code></strong> controls images. Most sites use
      <code>'self' data: https:</code> to allow same-origin images, data URIs (for
      icons/SVGs), and any HTTPS source (for user-uploaded content or CDNs).
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>font-src</code></strong> controls fonts. Common values include
      <code>'self'</code> and font CDNs like <code>https://fonts.gstatic.com</code>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>connect-src</code></strong> controls where your page can make
      network requests — <code>fetch()</code>, <code>XMLHttpRequest</code>, WebSocket,
      EventSource. If your app talks to APIs, this is where you list those origins.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>frame-src</code></strong> controls iframes that your page embeds
      (Stripe checkout, YouTube embeds, Google Maps).
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>frame-ancestors</code></strong> is the reverse: it controls who
      can embed <em>your</em> page in an iframe. This is the modern replacement for
      <code>X-Frame-Options</code>. Set it to <code>'none'</code> to prevent any
      framing, or <code>'self'</code> to allow same-origin only.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>form-action</code></strong> restricts where forms on your page
      can submit. Setting it to <code>'self'</code> prevents phishing attacks where
      injected forms post user data to attacker-controlled servers.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>base-uri</code></strong> restricts URLs in the
      <code>&lt;base&gt;</code> element. Most sites should set this to
      <code>'self'</code> to prevent attackers from changing relative URLs by
      injecting a <code>&lt;base&gt;</code> tag.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong><code>object-src</code></strong> controls <code>&lt;object&gt;</code>,
      <code>&lt;embed&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;applet&gt;</code> (Flash-era plugins).
      Setting it to <code>'none'</code> is recommended for almost every modern site.
    </p>

    <h3>Common source keywords</h3>
    <p>CSP source values can be exact URLs, wildcards, or special keywords:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>'self'</code> — same-origin (matches your protocol, host, and port)</li>
      <li><code>'none'</code> — no sources allowed</li>
      <li><code>'unsafe-inline'</code> — allows inline <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;style&gt;</code> blocks. <strong>Avoid in <code>script-src</code>.</strong></li>
      <li><code>'unsafe-eval'</code> — allows <code>eval()</code>, <code>new Function()</code>, and similar. <strong>Avoid universally.</strong></li>
      <li><code>'strict-dynamic'</code> — modern CSP3 mode that trusts scripts loaded by other trusted scripts</li>
      <li><code>data:</code> — allows <code>data:</code> URIs (inline images, fonts)</li>
      <li><code>blob:</code> — allows blob URLs (for dynamically generated content)</li>
      <li><code>https:</code> — allows any HTTPS source (broad — use sparingly)</li>
      <li><code>*</code> — wildcard. <strong>Essentially disables CSP.</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      You can also use scheme-host wildcards like <code>https://*.example.com</code>
      to allow all subdomains.
    </p>

    <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>

    <p class="faq-q">Will CSP break my Google Analytics?</p>
    <p class="faq-a">
      Possibly. If you load <code>gtag.js</code> from
      <code>https://www.googletagmanager.com</code>, you'll need to allow that in
      <code>script-src</code>. Google Analytics also makes XHR requests to
      <code>https://www.google-analytics.com</code>, so add that to
      <code>connect-src</code>. The CSP Builder's "Balanced" template handles common
      patterns like this.
    </p>

    <p class="faq-q">What's the difference between Content-Security-Policy and Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only?</p>
    <p class="faq-a">
      The enforcing header blocks resources that violate the policy. The report-only
      header logs violations to the browser console (and optionally to a
      <code>report-uri</code> endpoint) but doesn't block anything. Use report-only
      mode while testing your policy, then switch to enforcing once you're confident.
    </p>

    <p class="faq-q">Can I use both headers at the same time?</p>
    <p class="faq-a">
      Yes, and it's a useful pattern. Ship an enforcing header with your known-good
      policy, and ship a stricter report-only header to find places to tighten further.
      Browsers block based on the first and log based on the second.
    </p>

    <p class="faq-q">Do I need X-Frame-Options if I have frame-ancestors in my CSP?</p>
    <p class="faq-a">
      CSP <code>frame-ancestors</code> supersedes <code>X-Frame-Options</code> in
      browsers that support both (all modern browsers). For maximum compatibility,
      set both, but if you have to pick one, <code>frame-ancestors</code> is more
      flexible.
    </p>

    <p class="faq-q">How do nonces work?</p>
    <p class="faq-a">
      A nonce is a random value generated per-request. You include it in your CSP
      (<code>script-src 'nonce-abc123'</code>) and in the <code>nonce</code> attribute
      of every inline <code>&lt;script nonce="abc123"&gt;</code>. The browser only
      executes inline scripts whose nonce matches the header. Since the nonce changes
      every request, attackers can't predict it.
    </p>

    <h3>Further reading</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Security-Policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MDN — Content Security Policy</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Content_Security_Policy_Cheat_Sheet.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OWASP — CSP Cheat Sheet</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://csp-evaluator.withgoogle.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google — CSP Evaluator</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://web.dev/articles/strict-csp" target="_blank" rel="noopener">web.dev — Strict CSP guide</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://observatory.mozilla.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mozilla Observatory — full security audit</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Will CSP break my Google Analytics?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Possibly. If you load gtag.js from https://www.googletagmanager.com, you'll need to allow that in script-src. Google Analytics also makes XHR requests to https://www.google-analytics.com, so add that to connect-src. The CSP Builder's 'Balanced' template handles common patterns like this."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the difference between Content-Security-Policy and Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The enforcing header blocks resources that violate the policy. The report-only header logs violations to the browser console (and optionally to a report-uri endpoint) but doesn't block anything. Use report-only mode while testing your policy, then switch to enforcing once you're confident."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I use both Content-Security-Policy headers at the same time?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, and it's a useful pattern. Ship an enforcing header with your known-good policy, and ship a stricter report-only header to find places to tighten further. Browsers block based on the first and log based on the second."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I need X-Frame-Options if I have frame-ancestors in my CSP?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "CSP frame-ancestors supersedes X-Frame-Options in browsers that support both (all modern browsers). For maximum compatibility, set both, but if you have to pick one, frame-ancestors is more flexible."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do CSP nonces work?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A nonce is a random value generated per-request. You include it in your CSP (script-src 'nonce-abc123') and in the nonce attribute of every inline script tag. The browser only executes inline scripts whose nonce matches the header. Since the nonce changes every request, attackers can't predict it."
        }
      }
    ]
  })} />
</Layout>

<script>
  type Policy = Record<string, string[]>;

  const DIRECTIVES = [
    { id: 'default-src', desc: 'Fallback for other fetch directives when not specified.' },
    { id: 'script-src', desc: 'Sources allowed for JavaScript.' },
    { id: 'style-src', desc: 'Sources allowed for stylesheets.' },
    { id: 'img-src', desc: 'Sources allowed for images.' },
    { id: 'font-src', desc: 'Sources allowed for fonts.' },
    { id: 'connect-src', desc: 'Targets for fetch, XHR, WebSocket, EventSource.' },
    { id: 'media-src', desc: 'Sources for <audio> and <video>.' },
    { id: 'frame-src', desc: 'Sources allowed inside <iframe>.' },
    { id: 'frame-ancestors', desc: 'Which origins may embed this page in an iframe.' },
    { id: 'form-action', desc: 'URLs forms on this page may submit to.' },
    { id: 'base-uri', desc: 'Restricts URLs allowed in the <base> element.' },
    { id: 'object-src', desc: 'Sources for <object>, <embed>, <applet>. Set to \'none\' if unused.' },
  ];

  const QUICK_SOURCES = ["'self'", "'none'", "'unsafe-inline'", "'unsafe-eval'", "https:", "data:", "blob:", "*"];

  const RISKY: Record<string, string> = {
    "'unsafe-inline'": "Allows inline scripts/styles — defeats most XSS protection.",
    "'unsafe-eval'": "Allows eval() and similar — undermines CSP's main XSS protection.",
    "*": "Wildcard — allows any source. Essentially turns CSP off.",
    "https:": "Allows any HTTPS source. Very permissive.",
    "data:": "Allows data: URIs. Risky for script-src and style-src."
  };

  const TEMPLATES: Record<string, Policy> = {
    strict: {
      'default-src': ["'self'"],
      'script-src': ["'self'"],
      'style-src': ["'self'"],
      'img-src': ["'self'", "data:", "https:"],
      'font-src': ["'self'"],
      'connect-src': ["'self'"],
      'frame-ancestors': ["'none'"],
      'form-action': ["'self'"],
      'base-uri': ["'self'"],
      'object-src': ["'none'"]
    },
    balanced: {
      'default-src': ["'self'"],
      'script-src': ["'self'"],
      'style-src': ["'self'", "'unsafe-inline'"],
      'img-src': ["'self'", "data:", "https:"],
      'font-src': ["'self'", "data:"],
      'connect-src': ["'self'"],
      'frame-src': ["'self'"],
      'frame-ancestors': ["'self'"],
      'form-action': ["'self'"],
      'base-uri': ["'self'"],
      'object-src': ["'none'"]
    },
    permissive: {
      'default-src': ["'self'", "https:"],
      'script-src': ["'self'", "'unsafe-inline'", "https:"],
      'style-src': ["'self'", "'unsafe-inline'", "https:"],
      'img-src': ["*"],
      'font-src': ["*"],
      'connect-src': ["'self'", "https:"],
      'frame-src': ["'self'"],
      'frame-ancestors': ["'self'"]
    },
    empty: {}
  };

  let policy: Policy = clone(TEMPLATES.strict);
  let reportOnly = false;

  function clone<T>(o: T): T { return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(o)); }
  function escapeHtml(s: string) {
    return s.replace(/[&<>"']/g, c => ({ '&':'&amp;', '<':'&lt;', '>':'&gt;', '"':'&quot;', "'":'&#39;' }[c]!));
  }

  function renderDirectiveCard(d: typeof DIRECTIVES[number]): string {
    const enabled = d.id in policy;
    const sources = policy[d.id] || [];

    const sourcesHtml = enabled ? `
      <div class="sources-list">
        ${sources.length === 0
          ? `<span class="no-sources">No sources yet — add one below.</span>`
          : sources.map(s => `
            <span class="source-chip ${RISKY[s] ? 'risky' : ''}" title="${RISKY[s] ? escapeHtml(RISKY[s]) : ''}">
              ${escapeHtml(s)}
              <button type="button" class="chip-remove" data-remove-source="${escapeHtml(s)}">×</button>
            </span>
          `).join('')}
      </div>
      <div class="quick-add-row">
        ${QUICK_SOURCES.map(s => `
          <button type="button" class="quick-btn ${sources.includes(s) ? 'active' : ''} ${RISKY[s] ? 'risky' : ''}" data-quick-source="${escapeHtml(s)}">${escapeHtml(s)}</button>
        `).join('')}
      </div>
      <div class="custom-add">
        <input type="text" placeholder="https://example.com or https://*.example.com" data-custom-input />
        <button type="button" data-custom-add>Add</button>
      </div>
    ` : `<p class="disabled-note">Disabled — this directive is not included in the policy.</p>`;

    return `
      <article class="directive-card ${enabled ? '' : 'disabled'}" data-directive="${d.id}">
        <header class="directive-header">
          <div>
            <h3>${d.id}</h3>
            <p class="directive-desc">${escapeHtml(d.desc)}</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="toggle-btn ${enabled ? 'on' : 'off'}" data-toggle aria-pressed="${enabled}">
            ${enabled ? 'ON' : 'OFF'}
          </button>
        </header>
        ${sourcesHtml}
      </article>
    `;
  }

  function policyString(): string {
    return Object.entries(policy)
      .filter(([_, s]) => s.length > 0)
      .map(([d, s]) => `${d} ${s.join(' ')}`)
      .join('; ');
  }

  function policyMultiline(): string {
    return Object.entries(policy)
      .filter(([_, s]) => s.length > 0)
      .map(([d, s]) => `${d} ${s.join(' ')};`)
      .join('\n');
  }

  function renderAll() {
    const grid = document.getElementById('builder-grid')!;
    grid.innerHTML = DIRECTIVES.map(renderDirectiveCard).join('');

    const out = document.querySelector('#policy-output code')!;
    const ml = policyMultiline();
    out.textContent = ml || '/* No directives enabled. Pick a template or toggle a directive on. */';

    const headerName = reportOnly ? 'Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only' : 'Content-Security-Policy';
    const oneLine = policyString();

    const nginx = oneLine
      ? `add_header ${headerName} "${oneLine}" always;`
      : '# Policy is empty';
    const apache = oneLine
      ? `Header always set ${headerName} "${oneLine}"`
      : '# Policy is empty';
    const cloudflare = oneLine
      ? `# Cloudflare Dashboard → Rules → Transform Rules → Modify Response Header\n# Header name:  ${headerName}\n# Header value: ${oneLine}`
      : '# Policy is empty';

    (document.getElementById('snippet-nginx-code')!).textContent = nginx;
    (document.getElementById('snippet-apache-code')!).textContent = apache;
    (document.getElementById('snippet-cloudflare-code')!).textContent = cloudflare;
  }

  // Event delegation
  document.addEventListener('click', async (e) => {
    const t = e.target as HTMLElement;

    // Template buttons
    const tplBtn = t.closest('[data-template]') as HTMLElement | null;
    if (tplBtn) {
      const tpl = tplBtn.dataset.template!;
      policy = clone(TEMPLATES[tpl] || {});
      renderAll();
      return;
    }

    // Toggle directive
    if (t.matches('[data-toggle]')) {
      const card = t.closest('.directive-card') as HTMLElement;
      const id = card.dataset.directive!;
      if (id in policy) {
        delete policy[id];
      } else {
        policy[id] = ["'self'"];
      }
      renderAll();
      return;
    }

    // Remove source
    if (t.matches('[data-remove-source]')) {
      const card = t.closest('.directive-card') as HTMLElement;
      const id = card.dataset.directive!;
      const src = t.dataset.removeSource!;
      policy[id] = policy[id].filter(s => s !== src);
      renderAll();
      return;
    }

    // Quick add (toggle on/off)
    if (t.matches('[data-quick-source]')) {
      const card = t.closest('.directive-card') as HTMLElement;
      const id = card.dataset.directive!;
      const src = t.dataset.quickSource!;
      if (policy[id].includes(src)) {
        policy[id] = policy[id].filter(s => s !== src);
      } else {
        policy[id].push(src);
      }
      renderAll();
      return;
    }

    // Custom add
    if (t.matches('[data-custom-add]')) {
      const card = t.closest('.directive-card') as HTMLElement;
      const id = card.dataset.directive!;
      const input = card.querySelector('[data-custom-input]') as HTMLInputElement;
      const val = input.value.trim();
      if (val && !policy[id].includes(val)) {
        policy[id].push(val);
        renderAll();
      }
      return;
    }

    // Tab switching
    if (t.classList.contains('tab-btn')) {
      const target = t.dataset.target;
      if (!target) return;
      const block = t.closest('.fix-snippets')!;
      block.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn').forEach(b => b.classList.remove('active'));
      block.querySelectorAll('.tab-panel').forEach(p => p.classList.remove('active'));
      t.classList.add('active');
      block.querySelector('#' + target)?.classList.add('active');
      return;
    }

    // Copy button
    if (t.classList.contains('copy-btn')) {
      const panel = t.closest('.tab-panel');
      const code = panel?.querySelector('pre code')?.textContent;
      if (!code) return;
      try {
        await navigator.clipboard.writeText(code);
        const original = t.textContent;
        t.textContent = 'Copied!';
        t.classList.add('copied');
        setTimeout(() => { t.textContent = original; t.classList.remove('copied'); }, 1800);
      } catch {
        t.textContent = 'Copy failed';
      }
      return;
    }
  });

  // Handle Enter key in custom input
  document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    if (e.key !== 'Enter') return;
    const t = e.target as HTMLElement;
    if (!t.matches('[data-custom-input]')) return;
    e.preventDefault();
    const card = t.closest('.directive-card') as HTMLElement;
    const addBtn = card.querySelector('[data-custom-add]') as HTMLButtonElement;
    addBtn?.click();
  });

  // Report-only toggle
  document.getElementById('report-only')?.addEventListener('change', (e) => {
    reportOnly = (e.target as HTMLInputElement).checked;
    renderAll();
  });

  // Initial render
  renderAll();
</script>

